{"/service/ndnp/msar/batch_msar_nickel_ver01/data/sn87065528/00383345236/1949052701/0477.xml":{"full_text":"EASTON KING\u2014Editor and Manager\nIRENE KING, Associate Editor\nPublished Every Friday at Pascagoula, Mississippi, By\nTHE ADVERTISER PUBLISHING COMPANY\nPublication Office\u2014310-212 Deimas Avenue, Pascagoula, Mississippi\nEntered at the post office, Pasrsgnula. Mis*., April 29. 1921, under Act of March\n3, 1879, a* second class mail matter.\nEntered at the post office, Moe* Point, Ml**., October 8, 1909 under Act of\nMarch 3. 1879. as second class mall matter\nSUBSCRIPTION RATES: In Jackson Countv. 1 year *2 50; 8 mo *1 50. In state,\nI year S3 00; t mo S2.0O Outside elate, 1 year $3.50; 8 mo. $2 50 Single copy 10c\nSubscribers having their paper changed from one address to another should\ngive old address as well as the new.\nCards of Thanks, Resolutions. Memorials, Ohltuarles, Notices of Entertainments\nwhere admission Is to he charged, or other Notices not of General\nMaws value, will be charged for at adverUslng ratea.\n\"What State Line, What Law\nA strange case of buck passing surrounds the continu\ned and uninterrupted operation of the Sage Patch out in\nthe area known as the Free State of State Line. The Sage\nPatch runs wide open dice tables, slot machines, king\nsize bingo pots and what have you. Uncertainty as to\nwhether or not it is in Mississippi or Alabama is the reason\nlocal law enforcement officers cannot touch it, we are told.\nThis question of the location of the state line was to\nhave been settled three years ago by Attorney General\nGreek L. Rice after the 1946 legislature appropriated $.r>,0!)()\nfor a \u201cfriendly\u201d suit with the State of Alabama to estab\nlish the line, Legislative action was taken at the request\nof Attorney General Rice.\nNow comes an amazing twist to the circumstances,\nmore than three vears after the appropriation was made\namid hullabaloo and fanfare and statements as to what was\ngoing to be done.\nWe quote in full a letter addressed to L, K. McIntosh\nof Moss Point under date of May 17, 1949, over the signa\nture of Attorney General \"Rice:\n\u201cHonorable L. K. McIntosh\n\"Attorney at Law\n\"Moaa Point, Misslaaippl.\n\"Dear Mr. Mclntoah:\n\"I have your letter of May 14, 1949, about the suit\nagainst the State of Alabama, to establish the line between\nMiaaisalppi and Alabama, as authorized by Chapter 114 and\nChapter 319, Laws of 1946.\n\"You are advised that I have made a careful Investi\ngation of this matter and reached the conclusion that the\nsuit would hardly be iustiilod. It would cost so much money\nand, from my investigation. I found no real need for the\nre-establishment of this boundary line. The Governor and\nI agreed that the suit should not be brought.\n\"The appropriation made lor this suit has lapsed and\nbefore a. suit could be iiled another appropriation would\nbav\u00ab tg be made.\nYours very truly,\n\"Greek L. Rice.\"\nNow Jet's review the record of General Rice's State\nments at the time the bill authorizing the survey was pass\ned more than three years ago.\nOn March 13, 1946, the bill authorizing the survey was\nintroduced in the Mississippi House by J. Guy Krebs, then\nfloater representative for Jackson and Harrison counties\nand now sheriff. An Associated Press dispatch of that date\nsays:\n\"The bill provides that the survey would he made un\nder the direction of the Governor. Cost would be borne\njointly by the two states. It also authorizes a friendly\ncase in the United States supreme court to validate the\nline agreed upon by the two states.\n\"The bill was drawn by Attorney General Greek L.\nRice after he and William McQuoen, attorney general for\nAlabama, had conferred on tho matter.\"\nThen on March 14 another Associated Press dispatch\nout of Montgomery, Ala., read as follows:\n\"The US Supreme Court will hi' asked to settle the\nAlabama-Mississippi lxiundary dispute, Attorney General\nWilliam M. McQueen (of Alabama) said today.\n\"McQueen said he and G. I,. Rice, attorney general of\nMississippi, had agreed to let tin- latter slate file action in\nthe nation\u2019s highest court. McQueen and Assistant Attor\nney General Plmne F. Osborn conferred with Rice last\nweek at Jackson.\u2019\u2019\nNow wc quote from a news story in the Chronicle-Star\nand Advertiser dated March 15, 1946:\n\"Concrete steps were taken this week in the move to\nestablish the Eastern boundary of Mississippi to protect\nthe state\u2019s oil rich tidal lands and end the reign of lawless\nness in the \u2018Free State of State Line.\u2019\n\"Attorney General Greek L. Rice told the Chronicle\nStar and Advertiser (over tho long*distance telephone) that\nhe and Alabama Assistant Attorney General Prime F. Os\nborn had agreed at a Jackson mooting to let the United\nStates Supreme Court settle tho boundary dispute by Mla\naissippi filing a \u2019friendly\u2019 suit against Alabama.\nAlabama is as anxious to have the matter settled aB\nwe are,\u2019 Mr. Rice said. \u2018Mississippi is filing the action only\nbecause our legislature Is in session and it will expedite\nthe settlement\u2019.\"\nmen, aimosi a year later, on February lit, lim, an\nAssociated Press dispatch out of Jackson, Miss., had this to\nsay:\n\u201cAttorney Genera! Greek L. Rice said today that he\nwas going to Montgomery in May when the Alabama leg\nislature convenes in regular session where hp will seek to\nget enacted a bill by that state to pave the way for legal\nsettlement of the Alnbama-Mississippi state line.\n\u201cThe Mississippi legislature a year ago passed a hill\nsetting up machinery in the state for settlement of the K10\nyear-old dispute which grew out of an ambiguous survey\nand description of the line in the Mississippi constitution.\u201d\nDespite editorial prodding and unanswered questions,\nnothing more was heard about the State Line matter until\nGeneral Rice's letter of the other day.\nIt is hard to understand why, in the face of the above\nrecord and statements, that General Rice now says that\nsuch a suit would not be justified. Certainly if later inves\ntigation showed it was not justified, then it was not justi\nfied in the beginning. Why, then, did General Rice go to\n>\u00abi\nWML\nThe Democratic controlled\nSenate is giving the same run\naround to the bill that would\nrepeal the outrageous and dis\ncriminatory taxes on oleomar\ngarine as did the Republican\ncontrolled Senate last year.\nThe House has passed the bill,\nbut due to a \"press of legisla\ntion\" leaders predict that it\nwill die in the senate without\naction. That is exactly what\nhappened last year. The \"pi ess\nof legislation\" stripped of its\nwolf's clothing is the same old\nbutter and dairy lobby making\nthe same old political deal. The\ntaxes on oleo, which allows the\ndairy interests to maintain but\nter at inflated prices, will con\ntinue because the Senate plays\nits same sordid game of \u201cyou\nscratch my back and I'll scratch\nyours,\" and it makes little dif\nference whether they\u2019re Demo\ncrats or Republicans.\n\nIt's a funny world. Grand\nDragon Samuel Green of the\nKu KIux Klan screams viola\ntion of civil rights because the\nmayor of a small Georgia town\nhad the courage to rip the\nmasks off the faces of three\nKluxers and jailed them on\ncharges of disturbing the peace.\nThe sneaking, bully-boy, strong\narmed tactics of the Kluxers\nhave been responsible for more\nbrutality and violation of basic\ncivil rights than possibly any\nother organization in the Unit\ned States. If we had more pub\nlic officials like the above may\nor, we\u2019d have fewer members\nof the Klan.\n\nWhat, we wonder, has become\nof Elizabeth Bentley who was\nthe main attraction in the three\nring circus staged by the un\nAmerican Affairs Committee\nlast year. Miss Bentley, a blow\nzy female psychopathic who\nwas billed as a \u201cglamorous\u201d\nCommunist spy, accused virtu\nally every public official in\nWashington of being a Commu\nnist or at least a fellow-travel\ner. One of these, William Rem\nington, was the center of an at\ntack by the un-American Com\nmittee. On the unsubstantiat\ned testimony of Miss Bentley,\nhe was accused of being a Com\nmunist and suspended from his\njob. The daily press headlined\nthis from one end of the na\ntion to the other. Remington\ncarried his case before a loyal\nty review board, one of whose\nmembers was a former nation\nal commander of the American\nLegion. Two dates were set for\nMiss Bentley to appear before\nthe board and repeat her charge\nagainst Remington. She failed\nto appear either time. Reming\nton presented testimony in his\nown behalf and was cleared of\nthe charges by the board, re\ninstated in his job and given\nback pay. Most of the daily\npress buried this part of the\nstory under small headlines\nback with the classified ads.\nMeanwhile Miss Bentley has\nreturned to the obscurity from\nwhich she momentarily sprang\nto the un-American Committee\ncircus platform to do irrepara\nble damage to the reputations\nof innocent people.\n\nEconomy, as usual, is some\nthing Congress loves to talk\nabout (as long as it concerns\nthe other fellow) but when it\ncomes to laying it on the line,\nthat\u2019s a different matter. Every\neffort to pare expenditures in\n\u201cpork barrel\" measures has met\ninstant defeat. Big money bills\ncontaining many a \u201cpork bar\nrel\" measure have been passed\nintact. However, we suspect\nthat Congress will become\neconomy minded when the fed\neral housing bill conies up for\naction, or other measures gen\nerally tied to the welfare and\nsocial progress of the people\ninstead of pet local projects\nwhich bring votes.\n\nHurricanes during the oast\ntwo years have left Pascagoula\nwith little sand beach. We hope\nthis will be rectified when the\ncounty dredge is completed,\nthe trouble of drawing a bill and entering into several con\nferences with Alabama state officials?\nMeanwhile, the Sage Patch has continued serenely on\nits way, with no effort made to bring it under control of\nthe laws of the State of Mississippi.\nWe are dealing with facts here, and facts only. We are\ntold that local law enforcement officers cannot interfere\nwith the Sage Patch because of the uncertainty as to\nwhether it is located in Mississippi or Alabama.\nThe 1949 Jackson county assessment rolls show the fol\nlowing:\nThe Sage Patch Cafe, across Highway 90 from the Sage\nPatch Club, is assessed at $2,500 for stock, furniture and\nfixtures.\nThe Sage Patch Club is carried on the 1949 Jackson\ncounty assessment rolls at $2,900 for the same items.\nThe two buildings are carried on the 1949 Jackson\ncounty assessment rolls at $4,500.\nPerhaps this is not conclusive proof that the buildings\nare in Jackson county. Undoubtedly, some of the disputed\nland is also carried on the Mobile county assessment rolls.\nHowever, the assessment blanks for both the Sage\nPatch Cafe and the Sage Patch Club were signed in the\nname of the owner. This certainly leads us to believe that\nthe owner is at least partially convinced that the establish\nments are in Mississippi.\nWe will continue our analyzation of the Free State of\nState Line situation in another editorial next week.\n\"Pork Barrel Polka\" Again\n\nOne of the rankest pieces of \u201cpork barrel\" legislation\npassed by Congress in many a term is the bill which author\nizes an appropriation of $40 million dollars for the ac\nquisition of sites and advance planning for a new postoffice\nbuilding or the \"equivalent\u201d in each of the nation\u2019s 435\ncongressional districts.\nThe bill breezed through the economy-talking Con\ngress with virtually no opposition.\nNo new postoffices have been built during the past\n10 years and there is no question of need both of new build\nings and expansion of existing facilities. However, the\npresent bill makes no provision for study of these needs.\nThere has been considerable population shift during the\npast 10-year period, caused by the location of war industries\nthat have converted to peacetime production, and other\nfactors. Some congressional district undoubtedly could\nshow dire need for not one, but two, three or four new\nbuildings. Also, undoubtedly, others have no need for\nadditional buildings or facilities.\nThe present bill ignores this fundamental need for a\nnation-wide survey and simply allots a new building or its\n\u201cequivalent\" as a piece of political patronage to every one\nof the 435 members of Congress.\nThe Congressmen have taken care of themselves in\nanother way too. It might, be embarrassing to allot a build\ning to one section of a congressman\u2019s district, thereby\ncreating resentment in other sections. Therefore, the bill\nprovides that the federal works administrator and the\npostmaster general shall select the sites. In this manner\nthe Congressmen can work behind the scenes and at the\nsame time shift the burden of blame.\nIt\u2019s the old \u201cPork Barrel Polka\" being played with\npublic funds.\nLetters Europe's Recovery Program\nEditor.\nChronicle-Star,\nDear Sir:\nOn May 13th a group of the\nHurley school patrons met to\nprotest the dismissal, by two of\nthe trustees, of Mr. J. J. Mel\nvin, principal of the school for\nthe past three years.\nPrior to this meeting a peti\ntion signed by 264 patrons (90\nper cent) had been presented\nto the trustees requesting them\nto retain Mr. Melvin as he had\ndone an exceedingly good job\nas a principal. The building and\nschool grounds have been im\nproved under his guidance and\nscholastically the school has\nalso advanced. He is also very\nactive in church and commu\nnity activities. It is to be re\ngretted that the community is\nto lose an outstanding school\nman.\nSince the interest of our\nschool is of first importance\nwe pledge to the new principal\nour full co-operation and sup\nport in maintaining the high\nstandards and efficiency estab\nlished by Mr. Melvin.\nRespectively yours,\nA. N. Schmitz\nAxel C. Pederson\nC. E. Baria.\nBy CLARKE BEACH\nWASHINGTON European\nmoney has gone to work on a\nvast scale to make the Marshall\nPlan a success. The $5,000,000,\n000 of Marshall Plan funds pro\nvided so far is only a sixth or\nseventh of what Europe itself\nis spending to get back on its\nfeet.\nBefore the plan got started,\nthe bulk of the European money\nsupply was becoming dammed\nup, idle, thwarted. Without the\ndollars needed to buy certain\nessential western hemisphere\nproducts, native money resourc\nes could not go to work to re\nbuild the European economy.\nIn most of Europe the money\nwas willing to work, but it\nneeded help from the dollars.\nIn some countries the native\nmoney had lost its nerve.\nDavid Bruce, chief of the Eco\nnomic Cooperation Administra\ntion\u2019s (ECA) special mission to\nFrance, says that economic stag\nnation seized France in the\nl!)30's.\nThe value of the franc kept\nfalling until the last few months\nNot wanting to keep their mon\ney in francs, the investors\nbought hoards of goods\u2014such as\nrugs, jewelry, and paintings.\nSome rich people shipped goods\nabroad on consignment. The\nshippers kept title while the\ncommodities were held for them\nin foreign warehouses. The idea\nwas to eventually follow the\ngoods out of the country.\nThe big change in France\ncame early this year. The gov\nIn Western Germany there\nhas been a scarcity of invest\nment capital, but to ECA offi\ncials the money supply seems to\nprovcment has been noted yet,\nalthough the lira has held its\nprice for about a year now.\nernment announced it would\nseek new money in a 300,000.\n000,000 franc bond issue\nFriends of France held their\nbreath. If the people failed to\nsubscribe to the loan, it would\nshow they had no faith in their\nown government\u2019s financial sta\nbility. The value of the franc\nmight have dropped out of sight\nand the recovery effort would\nhave been dealt a serious blow.\nBut the bond issue was a\nhuge success. The value of the\nfranc immediately began to\nrise. Another good sign: The\nprice of gold on the French\nblack market has been falling\never since the bond issue. The\nprice had been boosted by farm\ners who had chosen to buy gold\nrather than risk holding on to\nfrancs. Now it seemed they\nwere unloading gold and choos\ning francs.\nUp to now most of the recov\nery plan investments in France\nhave been made by the Amer\nican feovernment because priv\nate capital was unwilling to\ntake the chance. Now the ex\nperts expect to see private in\nvestors get into the field.\nIn Italy the investment situ\nation has been much the same\nas in France. No marked im\nbe increasing as the balance of\nexports over imports continues\nto rise.\nGreece alone of the coun\ntries being helped has shown\nno improvement on the invest\nment side, according to ECA\nofficials. The continuing war\nfare\u2019there drains the resources\nof the nation.\nBut for the Marshall Plan\ncountries as a whole there is a\ngreat outpouring of native in\nvestment capital. They will\nspend about $30,000,000,000 this\nfiscal year to modernize facto\nries and farms, build new plants\nhomes and transportation fa\ncilities.\nThis means they will be tak\ning about 20 per cent of their\nnational incomes and plowing\nit back into business. In average\nperiods of prosperity such in\nvestment is usually around 15\nper cent ofdncome. To raise it\nto 20 per cent, the countries\nwill have to maintain reduced\nliving standards for some years\nyet, denying themselves a lot\nof consumer goods.\nThe business outlook has to\nbe good, and the people\u2019s faith\nin their countries\u2019 future must\nbe strong to impel them to in\nvest on such a scale. Even in\nthe United States in some years\nof the depression '30s the de\npreciation of plant values was\nlarger than the total of gross\ninvestment.\nTHIS WEEK\nin Other Years\nFIVE YEARS AGO THIS\nWEEK. Lt. Claude Martin was\nreported missing in action\n62 men from Jackson county\nanswered the call to armed serv\nices in April A boating club\nwas organized and a program\nof races scheduled for sail boats\nNo editorial carried.\n\nFOUR YEARS AGO THIS\nWEEK, Miss Mary Guest chris\ntened the U. S. Sea Scorpion\nat an Ingslls launching\nFrederick Yon, Jr. and Jesse\nParker met their deaths in the\nfighting on Okinawa War\nproduction training courses\nwere slated to close the end of\nMay President Truman be\nstowed the nation\u2019s highest hon\nor, the Congressional Medal of\nHonor, on Sgt. Jake W. Lindsey\nof Lucedale at Washington cer\nemonies i Editorial: Action\nNot Whitewash Is Needed;\nurged the cleaning up of the\nVeterans\u2019 administration.\n\nTHREE YEARS AGO THIS\nWEEK, The City of Moss Point\nwas under quarantine for ra\nbies A wind storm hit sud\ndenly destroying hangar and\ndamaging planes at the county\nairport Coast train service\nwas interrupted by major strike\nAnola was chosen as the\nnew name for the former Jun\nior Woman\u2019s club Editorial:\nSigns are not Enough: criticizes\nthe highway department for\nmarking dangerous hiwav men\naces instead of repairing them.\n\nTWO YEARS AGO THIS\nWEEK. The school year ended\nwith a hundred and one Pas\ncagoula seniors receiving di\nplomas 58 candidates had\nannounced for county offices\nTwelve political rallies had\nbeen scheduled over a period\nof three weeks Editorial:\nWasted Oil, urged conservation\nlaws and their enforcement in\nthe development of Mississippi's\noil fields.\n\nA YEAR AGO THIS WEEK,\nA veteran\u2019s coop was formed\nmaking available means for\npumping in a new sand beach.\nMeanwhile, though, what little\nbeach we do have should be\ncleaned up so that adults and\nchildren can take advantage\nof it.\n\nWith water conditions right\nduring the past two weeks fish\nhave been biting virtually\neverywhere. Big strings of brim\nand green trout have reward\ned the efforts of fishermen in\nall the lakes, bayous and rivers\nin this section. John Dailey, at\nthe Singing river fishing camp,\nreported a brim weighing one\npound two-ounces caught in\nBuzzard\u2019s lake. This is a fruit\nful country in its natural re\nsources, and as we have point\ned out for many past years,\nshould be preserved at all costs.\nThe dry Summer season is ap\nproaching, and pollution, par\nticularily by the Masonite Cor\nporation at Laurel, will again\nbe a problem. It's too bad that\nresponsible state officials, par\nticularly the director of the\nstate game and fish commis\nsion, W'on't approach the pro\ngram intelligently and without\nfear or favor to work out a\nsolution that will preserve our\nstreams and rivers and at the\nsame time allow Masonite and\nothers responsible to operate at 1\na profit. It could be done. We\nwant our industries and the\nemployment they bring, but we\nalso want our streams and the\npleasure and employment that\nthey, too, bring.\nPolitics For The Economists\n\nBy CLARKE BEACH\nWASHINGTON The Presi\ndent\u2019s Council of Economic Ad\nvisors started out with a noble\nintention to keep out of pol\nitics. But now the advisers\nknow that a top official in\nWashington is bound to be in\npolitics regardless of whether\nhe wants to be.\nDr. Edwin G. Nourse, the\ncouncil\u2019s chairman, is reported\nto have sponsored, late in 1946,\nthe idea that the council should\nremain aloof from the machin\nery of government. The other\ntwo members of the council ac\nquiesced for a year and a half.\nThe council had been urged to\ntestify before the Congressional\nJoint Committee on the Eco\nnomic Report, to discuss with\nthe members of the council\u2019s\nsemi-annual statement to the\nPresident. But when Senator\nTaft, then committee chairman,\nwas told of the council\u2019s wish\nnot to be involved in a contro\nversy which was bound to have\npolitical implications, he did\nnot insist that they appear.\nBut last summer two of the\ncouncilmen began to talk. Leon\nH. Keyserling testified before a\ncongressional committee on be\nhalf of the administration's\nanti-inflation bill. John D. Clark\ntestified before another con\ngressional committee.\nWhen the new chairman of\nthe Joint Committee on the Eco\nnomic Report, Senator O\u2019Ma\nhoney, renewed the invitation\nto the council this session, Key\nserling and Clark agreed to tes\ntify. They ardently supported\nthe administration\u2019s anti-infla\ntion program, and the brick\nbats began to fly. Legislators,\nad writers, columnists and\nspeakers took issue with them.\nThey found it necessary to de\nfend their position publicly\nKeyserling even wrote a letter\nto a newspaper about it.\ncourse never lesmiea oetore\nCongress. But he began to make\nspeeches. Former Secretary of\nDefense Forrestal urged him to\ngive talks on economics at two\norientation courses in the Pen\ntagon, to be attended by top\nmilitary and civilian leaders.\nNourse was dubious and talked\nto President Truman about it.\nThe President is reported to\nhave told him to go ahead. The\nspeeches were to have been\noff-the-record. But when some\nof his listeners related what\nthey had heard, Nourse gave\nout copies in order to keep the\nrecord straight.\nHis second speech, on April\n5, touched off a political explo\nsion. He spoke of the North At\nlantic pact and of providing\narms for the pact nations. He\nsaid it wouldn't be economical\nly safe simply to add such an\nexpense to the present govern\nment budget. Promptly the\nfoes of the administration\nturned Nourse's argument to\ntheir own uses. Anti-Marshall\nPlan forces, anti- Atlantic Pact\nlegislators and economy-mind\ned members of Congress all\nfound ammunition in Nourse\u2019s\nfor the purchase of PH A houses\nA feature story described\nthe change over of the woolen\nmill to the production of cotton\nknit goods Youth, Inc. an\nnounced a three-day rally on\nthe beach for building funds.\nEditorial: Housing for Jack\nson county veterans; a wise\nmove and one of benefit to the\ncounty.\nsuggestions. Some observers\nthought they detected isolation\nism in administration circles or\nantagonism between the econ\nomists and the military leaders.\nThe President found it neces\nsary a couple of days later to\nsay flatly at his press confer\nence that he had no intention of\ndeducting the cost of Atlantic\nPact arms from the administra\ntion\u2019s present military budget.\nOne economist, commenting on\nNourse\u2019s unhappy position, said\nthe development proved \u2018\u2018it is\nimpossible to divorce politics\nfrom economics they are part\nof the same thing.\u201d\nMeanwhile a controversy con\ntinues within the council itself.\nKeyserling and Clark have sup\nported the President\u2019s plea for\nstand-by controls to combat any\nrenewal of inflation. Nourse,\nfeeling that we are now in a\nstate of healthy \u201cdisinflation\u201d,\ndoesn\u2019t feel that such controls\nshould now be adopted.\nThis kind of situation was\nanticipated by the Hoover Com\nmission on Organization of the\nExecutive Branch. The commis\nsion said the Council is handi\ncapped by being a multi-head\ned body. The commission recom\nmended that the council \"be\nreplaced by an Office of the\nEconomic Adviser and that it\nhave a single head.\u201d\nAn economist who worked\nwith the commission said that\nthis report was submitted to the\nWhite House before it was re\nleased and received a favorable\nreview.\nBLACK LIST STOPS DRINKING\nST. PETER PORT, Guernsey\n\u2014(AP)\u2014Guernsey men say the\nfinest cure for drunkness is the\n\u201cblack list.\u201d\nThat is simply a list of men\u2014\nand women\u2014who must not be\nserved with alcoholic drinks on\nthe 16,000 square mile island. And\nanyone disregarding it and sell\ning or giving a drink to a listed\nperson is liable to $200 fine or\nsix months\u2019 imprisonment. Ifs\na medieval practice that works\nso well it\u2019s been preserved.\nChief Inspector John Banne\nville of the Guernsey civil inves\ntigation department quoted one\nman black listed for the last two\nyears:\n\u201cIt is impossible for me to get\na drink on this island now. No\none dares serve me; no one ever\ndreams of asking me to have a\ndrink.\"\nSome are black-listed volun\ntarily; other are listed on magis\ntrates\u2019 orders for excessive drunk\nenness.\nThose on the black list are pho\ntographed holding a blackboard\non which is written his name and\nage and the period for which he\nis blacklisted. The sentence re\ncords that he is on the black list\nfor a period varying from one\nyear to life.\nThen copies of the photograph\nare sent to every hotel and bar\nproprietor on the island. It must\nnot be exhibited but every pro\nprietor must keep it near his bar\nfor quick reference.\nANNUAL GARDEN CLUB\nLUNCHEON\nThe annual Pascagoula Garden\nclub luncheon at which the offi\ncers for 1949-50 will be installed,\nwill take place at Beach Park at\n1:30 June 1. Members desiring to\nattend the luncheon should phone\nMrs. E. A. Talbott for reserva\ntions.\n\nREDS BLACK OUT WEATHER\nREPORTS\nSHANGHAI (AP) The\nCommunist \u201cbamboo curtain\u201d\naround North China extends to\nthe stratosphere. It not only con\ntains the news, but weather re\nports as well.\nMuch of Asia\u2019s weather is born\nin the high-pressure areas of\nSiberia. It often undergoes great\nchange as it crosses Manchuria\nand North China into the low\npressure areas of the south.\nFor this reason, accurate fore\ncasting requires regular reports\nfrom the north, but for the past\nseveral months the Communists\nhave blacked them out.\nForecasters no longer can de\npend on the data which once came\nregularly from Mukden, Tientsin,\nPeiping and other northern cen\nters. Except for a very rare re\nport from some pilot flying over\nRed territory, the weatherman\nthese days makes up his forecast\nlargely on a basis of past expe\nrience.\nBELGIUM HAS FLYING\nDIPLOMAT\nBANGKOK (AP) \u2014Louis de\nSan has a vast territory to cover\nas Belgium's charge d'affaires for\nSiam, Indochina and Malaya, but\nhe manages easily he shuttles\nabout by piloting a flivver plane\nover southeast Asia. Flying is\nnothing new to the 39-year-old\ndiplomat. He has 1,800 hours to\nhis credit, many as a British Roy\nal Air Force transport pilot dur\ning the war. Before the war, Louis\nde San was a glider pilot. In fact,\nde San was glider champion of\nBelgium and later, when a sec\nretary in Chungking, he set an\nAsian glider record for height.\nNow, when he makes his long\ner hops he flew to Bangkok\nin easy stages from his previous\npost in Teheran, Iran, two months\nago de San\u2019s attractive blonde\nwife Kiki, the former Leone\nAlice de Chaffol de Courcelles,\nhelps him pilot his plane.\nCZECHS EXTEND PHONE\nSERVICE\nPRAGUE (AP) Czechoslo\nvakia is extending its overseas\ntelephone connections, the Com\nmunist newspaper \u201cRude Pravo\u201d\nsays. In addition to facilities with\nmost of the countries of Europe\nand the United States, it listed\nthese as soon to be linked up:\nAlaska, Bahama Islands, Bar\nbados, Bermuda. Costa Rica, the\nDominican Republic. Guatemala,\nHaiti, Honduras. Jamaica, Nica\nragua, Panama, Puerto Rico, Sal\nvador and Trinidad.\nENGLISH GET HEALTH PLAN\nSPARE PARTS\nBIRMINGHAM, England\u2014(AP)\n\u2014Five thousand persons have ap\nplied for artificial eyes under\nBritain\u2019s socialized medicine plan.\nThere have been 126,000 ap\nplications for surgical appliances.\nNearly 10,000 artificial legs have\nbeen ordered, and 3,000 supplied.\nC J. Simmons, parliamentary\nsecretary of the Ministry, dis\nclosed the figures in a speech\nhere. The Ministry of Pensions\nhandles such applications for the\nMinistry of Health, which admin\nisters the health plan.\nSimmons said one application\nfor an artificial leg was in behalf\nof an 18-months-old boy. The\nchild lost his leg in an automo\nbile accident. His name was not\ndisclosed. ____","height":"27780","width":"21828"}}
